<h2>How to Convert PDF to JPG on Windows</h2>

<h3>Using Microsoft Paint or Photos (Free)</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in Edge or Chrome.</li>
  <li>Take a screenshot of each page using the Snipping Tool (Win+Shift+S) and save as JPG.</li>
  <li>This works for single pages but is impractical for multi-page PDFs.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Using Adobe Acrobat Reader (Free)</h3>
<p>
  The free Adobe Acrobat Reader does not export to JPG — that requires Acrobat Pro (paid). Use the browser-based tool above for a free alternative.
</p>

<h3>Using Adobe Acrobat Pro (Paid)</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in Acrobat Pro.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>File → Export To → Image → JPEG</strong>.</li>
  <li>Choose output folder, resolution (72–300 DPI), and quality.</li>
  <li>Click <strong>Export</strong> — each page saves as a separate JPG.</li>
</ol>

<h2>How to Convert PDF to JPG on Mac</h2>

<h3>Using Preview (Built-in, Free)</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in <strong>Preview</strong>.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>File → Export</strong>.</li>
  <li>Change the Format dropdown to <strong>JPEG</strong>.</li>
  <li>Set the quality slider and click <strong>Save</strong>.</li>
</ol>
<p>
  Note: Preview exports one page at a time. For multi-page PDFs, this is slow. Use the browser tool for bulk conversion.
</p>

<h2>How to Convert PDF to JPG on iPhone or Android</h2>

