</ol>

<h2>Why Convert PDF to JPG?</h2>

<p>
  Understanding the use cases helps you decide if JPG is the right output format:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Social media sharing:</strong> Social platforms (Instagram, Twitter, LinkedIn) cannot display PDFs natively. Converting to JPG lets you share document content as images.</li>
  <li><strong>Embedding in Word or PowerPoint:</strong> You can insert a JPG image into Word or PowerPoint, but not a PDF page (on most platforms). Converting first makes embedding straightforward.</li>
  <li><strong>Email thumbnails:</strong> Send a JPG preview of a document as a quick visual teaser before attaching the full PDF.</li>
  <li><strong>Website display:</strong> HTML cannot embed PDFs as inline content in all browsers. JPG images are universally supported everywhere.</li>
  <li><strong>Printing single pages:</strong> Sometimes it is easier to print a JPG than a specific page from a multi-page PDF.</li>
</ul>

<h2>PDF to JPG vs PDF to PNG: Which Is Better?</h2>

<p>
  Both JPG and PNG are common image formats, but they serve different needs:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>JPG:</strong> Smaller file size, works well for photographic content and documents with images. Some quality loss due to compression. Best for web use and social media.</li>
  <li><strong>PNG:</strong> Lossless quality, supports transparency. Larger file size. Best for diagrams, screenshots, and documents with solid colours and sharp edges (like text and line art).</li>
</ul>
<p>
  For most PDF-to-image conversions, JPG is the practical choice. If you need pixel-perfect sharpness for a document with a lot of text and fine lines, PNG is better.
</p>

